{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}} '''Pace of play''' is an issue concerning [[college baseball]] and [[professional baseball]] regarding the length of games.
Game length in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) began increasing, with the [[1988 New York Yankees season|1988 New York Yankees]] being the first team to average over three hours per game.<ref name=cbs>{{cite web|last=Perry |first=Dayn |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/chart-the-rise-of-the-three-hour-baseball-game/ |title=CHART: The rise of the three-hour baseball game |publisher=CBSSports.com |date=August 27, 2014 |accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref> From 2004 through 2014, MLB games had increased from an average of 2.85 hours to 3.13 hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2014/09/mlb-games-length-three-hours-pace-of-play |title=Why are baseball games getting so much longer? &#124; For The Win |publisher=Ftw.usatoday.com |date=September 30, 2014 |accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref> This was in spite of decreases in scoring, with MLB teams scoring 4.1 runs per game in 2014, down from 5.14 in 2000.<ref name=cbs/>
In college baseball, the [[Southeastern Conference]] experimented with a 20-second [[pitch clock]] during the 2010 season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/gameon/post/2010/05/pitch-clock-for-baseball-experiment-begins-in-sec/1|title=Pitch clock for baseball? Experiment begins in SEC|work=USATODAY.COM|accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref> and the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] instituted the pitch clock before the 2011 season for when no runners are on base.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nola.com/tulane/index.ssf/2011/03/ncaa_rules_for_college_basebal.html |title=NCAA rules for college baseball are designed to speed up the game |publisher=NOLA.com |date=March 7, 2011 |accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref> During the 2014 season, the [[Atlantic League of Professional Baseball]] instituted its own changes. These included a 12-second pitch clock, reducing timeouts, warm-up pitches, making [[intentional walk]]s automatic by signalling the [[umpire (baseball)|umpire]], rather than throwing four intentional [[ball (baseball statistics)|balls]].<ref>https://www.si.com/mlb/2014/08/05/atlantic-league-pace-of-play-mlb</ref> The [[Arizona Fall League]] began using a pitch clock 2014 and the [[Double-A (baseball)|Double-A]] and [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] levels of [[Minor League Baseball]] followed suit in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pitch clock for Double-A, Triple-A use|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/12172716/mlb-use-pitch-clock-double-triple-games|website=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref> Those levels saw a 12-minute reduction in game times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20151009&content_id=152478810&fext=.jsp&vkey=toolshed&sid=milb|title=Minor League Baseball Toolshed: Pitch clocks do their job in debut season - MiLB.com News - The Official Site of Minor League Baseball|work=MiLB.com|accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref>
Towards the end of the 2014 season, [[Commissioner of Baseball]] [[Bud Selig]] announced the formation of a committee to examine the issue. [[John Schuerholz]] chaired the committee, which also included [[Sandy Alderson]], [[Tony Clark]], [[Rob Manfred]], [[Joe Torre]], and [[Tom Werner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2014/09/mlb-creates-committee-to-improve-pace-of-games |title=MLB creates committee to improve pace of games &#124; For The Win |publisher=Ftw.usatoday.com |date=September 22, 2014 |accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Manfred, having succeeded Selig as the Commissioner in 2015, instituted rule changes to MLB before the start of the [[2015 MLB season]] to address pace of play, including having batters remain in the [[batters box]] and the installation of time clocks to limit the time spent around [[commercial break]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ksdk.com/story/sports/2015/02/20/mlb-pace-of-play-rule-changes/23771199/|title=Rob Manfred thinks inside the box to speed up MLB games|date=February 20, 2015|work=KSDK|accessdate=June 10, 2015}}</ref> In 2015, MLB had a committee discuss bringing back the [[bullpen car]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/12568605/mlb-mlb-bring-back-bullpen-carts|title=Time to bring back bullpen carts?|work=ESPN.com|first=Jerry|last=Crasnick|date=March 31, 2015|accessdate=February 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/mlb-is-reportedly-considering-bringing-back-bullpen-carts-to-improve-pace-of-play/|title=MLB is reportedly considering bringing back bullpen carts to improve pace of play: Bullpen carts are viewed as a potential answer to the pace of play problem|first=R.J.|last=Anderson|publisher=CBS Sports|date=February 2, 2018|accessdate=February 24, 2018}}</ref>
Prior to the [[2017 MLB season]], the rules were amended to allow a [[manager (baseball)|manager]] to order an automatic intentional walk.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/sports/baseball-makes-intentional-walk-easier-faster-w468401|title=Major League Baseball Eliminates One of Its Most Annoying Rules|last=Rafferty|first=Scott|date=February 22, 2017|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=April 11, 2017|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> MLB and the [[MLB Players Association]] (MLBPA) discussed the possibility of introducing the pitch clock at the major league level for the 2018 season.<ref name=opinions>{{cite web|last=Castrovince |first=Anthony |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opinions-differ-on-mlb-pitch-clock/c-265068962 |title=Opinions differ on MLB pitch clock |publisher=MLB.com |date=January 20, 2016 |accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref> MLB opted against imposing it unilaterally, over the opposition of the MLBPA.<ref>{{cite web|author=USA TODAY Sports |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2018/02/19/mlb-no-pitch-clock-2018-but-mound-visits-warm-up-times-limited/351422002/ |title=MLB pace of play: No pitch clock in 2018, but mound visits limited |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=February 19, 2018 |accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Before the 2018 season, MiLB took major actions, including adding pitch clocks at all levels and beginning each [[extra inning]] with a runner on second base.<ref>{{cite web|author=THE ASSOCIATED PRESS|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/14/sports/baseball/minor-leagues-pace-of-play.html |title=Minor League Baseball Expands Pace-of-Play Rules - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date= |accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Also, the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] of MLB announced they would introduce their first bullpen car in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/22665199/arizona-diamondbacks-use-golf-cart-bring-relief-pitchers-2018|title=Golf cart to bring in relief pitchers is reborn with Diamondbacks|first=Darren|last=Rovell|work=ESPN.com|date=March 6, 2018|accessdate=March 6, 2018}}</ref>
